Jaccard similarity of filtered variants in all cell lines

Robert Allaway

05 October, 2022

To assess the similarities in mutational profiles across the cell lines, we can calculate the pairwise Jaccard similarity for all cell lines. First, we used the Strelka2 to call the variants, and then applied filters to further refine the list of variants (see filter_vcfs.sh).

Then, the concordance/Jaccard similarity was calculated using bedtools jaccard (see assess_concordance.sh). In this script, we retrieve the previously calculated jaccard metrics from Synapse, combine them into one file, and reformat so that we can plot a heatmap where 1 = identical variants and 0 = no overlapping variants.

note: the struck-through section below was actually an error identified in code review, and is not accurate

Notably, cell line 28NF had no variants that passed our filters. The QC data for the sequencing runs did not indicate any major issues with the data, so this suggests that no exome variants were detected. However, this is pretty unlikely, so its possible that the data are indeed problematic. We should revisit this analysis with the whole genome sequencing variants to see if we observe a similar phenomenon.

Other than the weird results with 28NF, the remainder of the results are encouraging. All of the immortalized cell lines cluster with their non-immortalized counterparts, and the cell lines from the same patient (e.g.97.2, 98.4) cluster together. This indicates that the immortalized cells maintain some level of genetic fidelity despite the genetic changes required to engineer these cell lines.

library(synapser)
library(tidyverse)
library(viridis)
library(pheatmap)
library(gt)
synLogin()
## Welcome, Robert Allaway!
## NULL
child <- synGetChildren('syn34227782')$asList()
ids <- map(child, "id") %>% unlist()

jac_temp <- sapply(ids, function(x){
 file <- synGet(x)$path %>% read_tsv(.) %>% unlist
}) %>% t() %>% as_tibble()

nms <- sapply(ids, function(x){
 file <- synGet(x)
 nm <- file$properties$name
}) 

jac <- jac_temp %>% 
  add_column("comparison" = nms %>% stringr::str_remove("_jaccard.tsv")) %>% 
  separate(comparison, into = c('cl1', 'cl2'), sep = "_")  

table_of_immortalized_cells <- jac %>% rowwise %>% filter(grepl(glue::glue("i{cl1}"), cl2)) %>% 
  select(cl1, cl2, jaccard) %>% 
  mutate(jaccard = round(jaccard, 3)) %>% 
  set_names("Primary cell line", "Immortalized cell line", "Jaccard index")

Lets also make a heatmap of the pairwise Jaccard similarity.

jac %>% 
  select(jaccard, cl1, cl2) %>% 
  pivot_wider(id_cols = cl1, names_from = cl2, values_from = jaccard) %>% 
  column_to_rownames("cl1") %>% 
  pheatmap::pheatmap(color = viridis::rocket(100, begin = 1, end = 0))

Finally, lets plot the individual similarities based on whether or not they are biologically related or not.

related_pairs <- jac %>% 
  mutate(related = case_when(stringr::str_extract(cl1, "\\d\\d") != stringr::str_extract(cl2, "\\d\\d") ~ FALSE,
                             stringr::str_extract(cl1, "\\d\\d") == stringr::str_extract(cl2, "\\d\\d") ~ TRUE)
         )  %>% #extracts matching numerals which indicates sample relatedness (e.g. 28cNF is from same patient as i28cNF, etc) and determines if they match, whether or not the samples are related
  filter(jaccard < 1) %>%  #remove self-self pairs
  select(cl1, cl2, n_intersections, jaccard, related) %>% 
  set_names("Cell Line 1", "Cell Line 2", "Number of overlapping variants", "Jaccard similarity (0 to 1)", "Related?")


ggplot(related_pairs, aes(x = `Related?`, y = `Jaccard similarity (0 to 1)`)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  ggbeeswarm::geom_quasirandom(alpha = 0.4) +
  theme_bw() + 
  ylim(c(0, 0.5))

related_pairs_2 <- mutate(related_pairs, Comparison = glue::glue("{`Cell Line 1`}_{`Cell Line 2`}")) %>% 
  mutate(Comparison = forcats::fct_reorder(Comparison, -`Jaccard similarity (0 to 1)`))


ggplot(related_pairs_2, aes(x = Comparison, y = `Jaccard similarity (0 to 1)`, fill =  `Related?`)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  theme_bw()+
  theme(axis.text.x  = element_text(angle = 45))
